WEBVTT

00:01.826 --> 00:11.076
Just this week, my dad sent me a link to an old song sung by a gospel singer who's one of his favorites.

00:13.719 --> 00:19.185
If you've heard the song, I would guess many in this room have not called his eye is on the sparrow.

00:20.827 --> 00:21.648
Okay, so a few.

00:23.590 --> 00:27.394
And the chorus goes, I sing because I'm happy.

00:27.414 --> 00:30.578
I sing because I'm free.

00:31.138 --> 00:36.323
for his eye is on the sparrow, and I know he watches me."

00:41.128 --> 00:46.833
That is often the case that we sing because we're happy.

00:48.715 --> 00:50.637
Song is often identified with joy.

00:54.120 --> 00:59.986
But my question here for us in these few minutes is, are there other reasons to sing

01:00.930 --> 01:02.893
than because we're already happy.

01:05.757 --> 01:19.215
The book of Psalms gives us saint after saint and Psalm after Psalm that weren't written from happiness, not immediately, not easy circumstances.

01:20.377 --> 01:22.880
They sang because they were sad.

01:24.162 --> 01:25.804
They sang because they were grieving.

01:25.844 --> 01:30.130
They sang from disorientation

01:30.306 --> 01:32.610
from confusion, from fear.

01:34.352 --> 01:37.557
They sang because they were lonely or guilty or ashamed.

01:39.480 --> 01:40.522
Now it's not all the Psalms.

01:42.104 --> 01:46.892
There are many Psalms of praise where they sing because they're happy.

01:47.713 --> 01:52.140
And Psalms of Thanksgiving where they sing because they feel gratitude.

01:52.861 --> 01:58.450
But more songs than not in the Psalms are what's called laments.

02:00.034 --> 02:02.878
50 or 60 of the 150 Psalms.

02:02.918 --> 02:15.654
The most common type of Psalm in the Bible is a lament where some grievous cause, some pain, some suffering, some sadness gives rise to the need and desire for singing.

02:15.714 --> 02:28.530
At the ministry of desiring God, we are committed to and we celebrate the pervasive biblical reality

02:28.706 --> 02:32.933
that God is most glorified in us when we're most satisfied in him.

02:35.176 --> 02:56.690
We think and believe the Bible teaches that the good shepherd looks really good when he sheep thrive, when they're happy, when they're contented, which raises a question for us and for all Christians,

02:57.954 --> 02:59.336
What about sadness?

03:00.738 --> 03:01.860
Maybe you came in here tonight.

03:02.560 --> 03:05.645
We're supposed to sing, magnify the Lord with me.

03:06.266 --> 03:09.570
You're carrying some sadness, some burden.

03:11.313 --> 03:26.354
If God is honored in his people's joy, how do we approach the many difficult circumstances in our lives, the unavoidable sorrows, the griefs that we face all the time?

03:26.882 --> 03:28.324
as Christians in this fallen world.

03:29.926 --> 03:35.553
To put a point on it is God dishonored when His people grieve.

03:38.316 --> 03:45.044
The sadness in God's people taint His glory in His people.

03:48.088 --> 03:56.018
In a few minutes here, we're going to sing together what we like to call our signature song, a desiring God.

03:57.058 --> 03:58.961
It is the hymn, it is well.

04:00.503 --> 04:03.968
Maybe more of you know that one than his eyes on the sparrow.

04:05.250 --> 04:10.757
And it is well, starts like this, when peace like a river, attended my way.

04:11.318 --> 04:12.840
That's good, peace, happy.

04:14.422 --> 04:22.674
And then when sorrows like sea billows roll, to imagine the waves,

04:22.914 --> 04:24.536
of sorrow that are coming.

04:24.596 --> 04:25.638
You see them coming.

04:25.898 --> 04:27.460
You know they're going over your head.

04:28.862 --> 04:35.991
Whatever my lot, God has taught us to say, it is well, it is well with my soul.

04:39.636 --> 04:45.643
Sorrows like sea billows have been especially real for my family here just this fall.

04:48.147 --> 04:50.770
We know four families very well.

04:52.514 --> 04:55.898
from our son's baseball, spent all summer with these families.

04:57.059 --> 05:11.476
And on the first day of school in late August, all the students are gathered for an opening mass at a Catholic school and a gunman shoots through the windows, enters hundreds of rounds into the room where there's 400 kids.

05:12.818 --> 05:16.382
My 10-year-old, net-year-old daughters have a nine-year-old friend.

05:16.422 --> 05:19.666
They've run around with it baseball games all summer, shot three times.

05:20.898 --> 05:30.090
all four families who we know well and have deeply in our lives had kids in the room when the gunman opened fire.

05:31.191 --> 05:32.833
And we have mourned with them.

05:32.853 --> 05:37.639
We felt the heaviness of it as close as we've been to one of these situations.

05:38.781 --> 05:49.074
And then not long afterwards, this is just last month, a dear friend of ours, 40 years old, father of three, coach, math teacher at the high school,

05:49.698 --> 05:56.064
A lay pastor who frequently preaches, fell, broke his neck.

05:57.285 --> 06:04.392
He was airlifted down to the Twin Cities where I live, and visited him the next night in the hospital.

06:04.412 --> 06:08.396
I think we've grieved with them in these last few weeks.

06:09.076 --> 06:19.346
And remarkably, when I first saw Jake in the ICU walk up our eyes meet, he says,

06:19.522 --> 06:22.565
And he's at this point paralyzed from his shoulders down.

06:22.605 --> 06:23.987
He has no feeling, no movement.

06:25.068 --> 06:31.215
He looks me in the eye and he says, I have my brain and I have my soul.

06:31.255 --> 06:39.284
And what I heard him communicating in that moment was eat as well with my soul.

06:39.324 --> 06:42.147
I want to live like that.

06:42.167 --> 06:44.089
I want to sing in those moments.

06:45.511 --> 06:48.434
When there's plenty of sorrows like sea bill is rolling,

06:49.890 --> 06:55.158
So let me be clear here where the sorrows and the sadness come from.

06:56.720 --> 06:59.204
That was not part of the original creation.

07:01.006 --> 07:09.739
Sorrow and sadness entered our world because of human sin and because of God's curse on our world, because of our sin.

07:09.799 --> 07:14.546
They remind us of the human sin in which we all share.

07:15.330 --> 07:21.780
And so that means that our sorrows in this age can be holy sorrows and unholy sorrows.

07:22.241 --> 07:22.942
This is important.

07:24.305 --> 07:32.478
Sometimes in our world, there's the assumption that all sorrows are bad or the counter argument that all sorrows must be good.

07:32.538 --> 07:37.927
But biblically, there's good sorrows and bad sorrows.

07:38.828 --> 07:42.514
So the Apostle Paul talks about excessive sorrow.

07:43.490 --> 07:45.272
in 2 Corinthians 2, 7.

07:46.013 --> 08:09.938
And on the other side of that, there can be insufficient sorrow, a time when you should mourn and you don't, or a misplaced sorrow, like the rich young ruler who heard from Jesus that he could have Jesus if he would just release his grasp on his stuff.

08:11.618 --> 08:20.332
And Luke 18 says, when he heard these things from Jesus, he became very sad for he was extremely rich.

08:21.614 --> 08:28.946
Jesus, seeing that he had become sad, said how difficult it is for those who have wealth to enter the kingdom of God.

08:30.208 --> 08:32.271
That's misplaced sorrow.

08:32.291 --> 08:34.034
That is not holy sorrow.

08:35.837 --> 08:37.379
But not all sadness is unholy.

08:38.461 --> 08:39.122
Far from it.

08:39.906 --> 08:45.635
The Bible gives us examples over and over again of holy, godly, appropriate, mature sorrow.

08:46.917 --> 08:50.903
Like grief over the unbelief of loved ones.

08:51.544 --> 08:52.746
Like Paul in Romans 9.

08:53.367 --> 08:57.073
Or grief over a final parting with somebody you love.

08:57.954 --> 08:58.675
Like Acts 20.

08:59.697 --> 09:03.142
Or grief over the death of someone you love.

09:03.503 --> 09:04.384
That's appropriate.

09:04.945 --> 09:05.926
It's good sorrow.

09:07.188 --> 09:08.210
Or grief

09:08.610 --> 09:12.615
over unjust suffering because of Jesus.

09:13.376 --> 09:16.300
This is 1 Peter chapter 2 verse 19.

09:17.282 --> 09:26.334
This is a gracious thing when mindful of God one endures sorrows while suffering unjustly.

09:27.035 --> 09:27.696
It's a good thing.

09:27.736 --> 09:33.864
It's a gracious thing to endure suffering for Jesus' sake, mindful of God and endure those sorrows.

09:35.747 --> 09:38.290
And there's grief over our sin.

09:39.682 --> 09:43.668
The kind of grief Paul says that leads to repentance.

09:43.688 --> 09:54.203
In 2 Corinthians 7, I rejoice, he says, not because you were grieved, but because you were grieved into repenting, for you felt a godly grief.

09:55.304 --> 10:04.978
For godly grief produces a repentance that leads to salvation without regret, whereas worldly grief produces death.

10:06.722 --> 10:11.067
For see what earnestness this godly grief has produced in you.

10:12.328 --> 10:14.110
So godly grief.

10:14.130 --> 10:16.833
Holy sorrow is not like the world's grief.

10:19.476 --> 10:29.808
So very memorably, in 1 Thessalonians 4, Paul talks about Christians not grieving like those who have no hope.

10:31.430 --> 10:33.412
It's a different grief.

10:33.432 --> 10:35.474
And Paul doesn't say to Christians, don't grieve.

10:36.194 --> 10:37.356
You have Jesus, don't grieve.

10:38.898 --> 10:43.804
It says, there are real losses in this age, in this world of sin and curse.

10:44.165 --> 10:44.766
We grieve.

10:46.648 --> 10:48.791
And we don't grieve like the world without hope.

10:49.312 --> 10:50.534
We grieve with hope.

10:52.256 --> 10:56.262
For the Christian hope is not a thin wish or a dream.

10:57.263 --> 11:02.811
Hope is confidence that the God who has made promises is going to make good on his promises.

11:04.954 --> 11:05.234
So,

11:05.762 --> 11:12.891
Grief and sorrow, that's what you came in here with tonight, or you've been through a season, or you haven't coming.

11:14.412 --> 11:26.928
Grief and sorrow in this age are not just allowable in the Christian life and in a room of worship, but it can be holy and even necessary.

11:28.369 --> 11:35.538
It is a good thing to cry at the right time, like

11:35.970 --> 11:39.834
the Man of Sorrows, who was acquainted with grief.

11:41.096 --> 11:42.778
Isaiah prophesied about Jesus.

11:43.719 --> 11:49.545
In John 11, his friend, who he loves, Lazarus, has died.

11:51.067 --> 11:55.892
When he comes to Bethany, he sees his sister Martha, then his sister Mary.

11:57.494 --> 12:04.402
John 11, when Jesus saw Mary weeping and the Jews who had come with her also weeping,

12:04.546 --> 12:08.470
He was deeply moved in his spirit and greatly troubled.

12:09.952 --> 12:11.994
And he said, where have you laid him?

12:12.034 --> 12:20.464
They said to him, Lord, come and see Jesus wept.

12:22.306 --> 12:28.633
So the Jew said, see how he loved him, which is a really good observation.

12:30.314 --> 12:33.618
You see love in grief.

12:34.594 --> 12:37.978
When you really love someone, you grieve their loss.

12:39.100 --> 12:43.225
What you grieve reveals what and whom you love.

12:46.429 --> 12:50.254
But Jesus didn't only feel our sorrows when he was among us.

12:51.375 --> 12:53.298
As they also said, he carried them.

12:54.600 --> 12:56.742
He bore our sorrows.

12:58.004 --> 13:01.048
He bore our griefs and carried our sorrows.

13:01.388 --> 13:02.770
Yet we esteemed him stricken.

13:03.042 --> 13:09.070
smitten by God and afflicted, but he was pierced for our transgressions.

13:09.090 --> 13:11.973
He was crushed for our iniquities.

13:12.674 --> 13:15.858
Upon him was the chastisement that brought us peace.

13:16.619 --> 13:20.023
And by his wounds, we are healed.

13:22.887 --> 13:31.538
And because of Jesus' work on our behalf, carrying our sorrows, bearing our griefs, a day is coming where there will be no more sorrows.

13:32.866 --> 13:34.809
Every tear will be wiped away.

13:35.911 --> 13:43.082
Death shall be no more, nor shall there be mourning, nor crying, nor pain anymore."

13:45.005 --> 13:50.153
And here's the way Isaiah talks about it all the way back 700 years before Jesus.

13:51.014 --> 13:58.546
He says, the ransomed of the Lord shall return and come to Zion with singing

14:00.098 --> 14:02.841
Everlasting joy shall be upon their heads.

14:03.242 --> 14:06.086
They shall obtain joy and gladness.

14:06.927 --> 14:10.611
And sorrow and sighing shall flee away."

14:12.654 --> 14:13.695
So that's the day that's coming.

14:15.618 --> 14:16.879
But that's not the day that's here yet.

14:18.982 --> 14:19.963
It's not where we live yet.

14:20.904 --> 14:21.745
Let me close with this.

14:23.528 --> 14:28.594
For now, how do joy and sorrow relate?

14:30.370 --> 14:36.357
On the one hand, they coexist in the Christian life.

14:37.999 --> 14:43.486
Paul talks in 2 Corinthians 6 about being sorrowful, yet always rejoicing.

14:44.968 --> 14:46.449
The sorrows didn't push the joy out.

14:48.091 --> 14:48.892
The joy was deeper.

14:49.653 --> 14:50.314
It was thicker.

14:51.155 --> 14:52.096
It helped him endure.

14:52.136 --> 14:53.158
They coexisted.

14:53.218 --> 15:00.146
So don't think that to have joy, you got to push out all the sorrows, or that when sorrows comes, it pushes out all the joy.

15:00.674 --> 15:03.096
They coexist in the Christian life.

15:04.518 --> 15:13.606
And in 1 Peter, chapter one, verses six and seven, he says, in the living hope of Jesus, risen from the dead.

15:13.626 --> 15:14.867
He's the living hope.

15:14.887 --> 15:25.557
In him, you rejoice, there's joy, though for a little while, if necessary, you have been grieved by various trials.

15:26.838 --> 15:30.642
You rejoice, though you're grieved.

15:32.642 --> 15:35.345
So joy and sadness coexist in the Christian life.

15:36.006 --> 15:44.136
And secondly and finally, sorrows now prepare us for greater joy to come.

15:44.917 --> 15:51.045
The joy will be greater in the end because of enduring sorrows now by faith.

15:52.126 --> 16:01.618
And so Paul says in 2 Corinthians 4, 17, that our slight momentary affliction is preparing for us an eternal weight of glory

16:02.050 --> 16:03.171
beyond all compares.

16:05.013 --> 16:15.325
In this age, that mingling of joy and sorrow in the Christian life is preparing for us an eternal weight of glory and its surpassing joy.

16:18.128 --> 16:28.199
At Desiring God, we have this phrase that we put with our favorite slogan about God is most glorified in us when we're most satisfied in Him.

16:28.739 --> 16:31.282
We had this phrase, especially

16:31.522 --> 16:32.303
in suffering.

16:34.024 --> 16:36.787
We don't say even in suffering.

16:36.807 --> 16:37.468
We could say that.

16:37.608 --> 16:37.988
That's true.

16:38.148 --> 16:38.829
Even in suffering.

16:39.490 --> 16:46.276
But more than just even, we say, especially in suffering.

16:46.296 --> 16:57.927
For now, willingness to experience sadness and sorrow is not a concession for joy-seeking Christians, but it's an opportunity.

16:59.649 --> 17:01.170
And it's even a necessity.

17:02.114 --> 17:11.204
For now, we cannot pursue the deepest and most enduring joy without a willingness to grieve the joys that we lose.

17:13.066 --> 17:18.552
And for now, we say especially in suffering.

17:18.572 --> 17:25.460
We experience sorrows like sea billows, and they are real sorrows, and we grieve them.

17:25.520 --> 17:26.661
Oh, we grieve them.

17:28.663 --> 17:31.026
And real joy in God enables us

17:31.842 --> 17:41.312
to grieve them and not drown in them because we can say eat as well with my soul.

17:42.814 --> 17:43.615
Would you pray with me?

17:45.577 --> 18:01.394
So Father in Heaven, as we reflect here on why we sing, many of us do sing because we're happy and many of us sing because we are seeking

18:01.666 --> 18:02.207
joy.

18:07.736 --> 18:09.980
Singing is not just an expression of wellness.

18:11.242 --> 18:14.247
Singing is because we want more of Jesus.

18:14.307 --> 18:17.132
We want to experience more of Him.

18:17.993 --> 18:19.235
So draw near to us now.

18:19.315 --> 18:28.050
Those who are happy and especially in suffering, especially in sorrows as we sing in Jesus' name.

